la: aedifico autem Saul altare Domini tunc primus coepio aedificaris altare Domini
en: And Saul built an altar to the Lord: and he then first began to build an altar to the Lord.

la: Quo magis hic homo timuerant, is gratus civilis tantus imperator redeo fuit: omnis quippe Brundisium dimitto exercitus nihil praeter nomen imperator retineo cum privo comitatu, qui semper ille astaris mos fuit, in urbs redeo magnificentissimumque de tot rex per biduus ago triumphus longus magnus omnis ante sui infero pecunia in aerarium, praeterquam ab Paulo, ex manubiae intulit.
en: The return of so great a general a an ordinary citizen wa all the more welcome because of the apprehension which had been entertained. For, dismissing his whole army at Brundisium, and retaining none of his former power except the title of imperator,a he returned to the city with only the retinue which regularly attended him. There he celebrated, for a period of two days, a most magnificent triumph over the many king whom he had conquered, and from the spoil he contributed to the treasury a far larger sum of money than any other general had ever done except Paulus.

la: et ab mensura iste mensuro longitudo viginti quinque mille et latitudo decem mille et in ipse sum templum sancio sancio
en: And with this measure thou shalt measure the length of five and twenty thousand, and the breadth of ten thousand, and in it shall be the temple and the holy of holies.

la: ibi tu pasco adhuc enim quinque annus residuus sum fames ne et tu pereo et domus tuus et omnis qui possideo
en: And there I will feed thee, (for there are yet five year of famine remaining) lest both thou perish, and thy house, and all thing that thou hast.

la: similis et princeps sacerdos illudo cum scribo et senex dico
en: In like manner also the chief priests, with the scribe and ancients, mocking said:

la: et dico Dominus ad Mosen extendo manus tuus in caelum ut fio grando in universus terra Aegyptius super homo et super iumentum et super omnis herba ager in terra Aegyptius
en: And the Lord said to Moses: Stretch forth thy hand towards heaven, that there may be hail in the whole land of Egypt upon men, and upon beasts, and upon every herb of the field in the land of Egypt.

la: et cum semino sum ascendo et fio magnus omnis holeribus et facio ramus magnus ita ut possum sub umbra is aveo caelum habito
en: And when it is sown, it groweth up, and becometh greater than all herbs, and shooteth out great branches, so that the bird of the air may dwell under the shadow thereof.

la: Cuius ille pietas plenus populus Romanus gratia refero ipse viritim civitas donando, duo filius is creo praetores, cum senex adhuc crearentur.
en: The Romans abundantly repaid his loyal zeal by a special grant of the citizenship to himself, and by making his son praetor at a time when the number elected wa still confined to six.

la: atque inde pertranseo in Asemona et pervenio ad torreo Aegyptius sum terminus is mare Magnus hic sum finis meridianus plaga
en: And from thence passing along into Asemona, and reaching the torrent of Egypt: and the bound thereof shall be the great sea, this shall be the limit of the south coast.

la: Suessa et in Lucanus plostra, treblae; Albae, Roma dolia, labra; tegula ex Venafro.
en: cart and sledge at Suessa and in Lucania; jar and pot at Alba and at Rome; and tile at Venafrum.

la: dormio cum pater suus et sepelierunt is in civitas David regno pro is Roboam filius is
en: And he slept with his fathers: and they buried him in the city of David: and Roboam his son reigned in his stead.

la: voco rex Ioas Ioiada pontifex et sacerdos dico is quare sarcio tectum non instauro templum nolo ergo amplus accipio pecunia iuxta ordo vester sed ad instauratio templum reddo is
en: And king Joas called Joiada, the high priest, and the priests, saying to them: Why do you not repair the temple? Take you, therefore, money no more according to your order, but restore it for the repairing of the temple.

la: quia ex nihilum nascor sum et post hic sum tamquam non sum quoniam fumus afflo sum in naris noster et sermo scintilla ad commoveo cor nos
en: For we are born of nothing, and after this we shall be a if we had not been: for the breath in our nostril is smoke: and speech a spark to move our heart,

la: et ad-sumo ego spiritus et audio post ego voco commotio magnus benedico gloria Domini de locus suus
en: And the spirit took me up, and I heard behind me the voice of a great commotion, saying: Blessed be the glory of the Lord, from his place.

la: mortuus itaque primus ille hic modo sequor deduco ad illudo et cutis capio is cum capillus detraho interrogo si manduco priusquam totus corpus per membrum singulus punior
en: So when the first wa dead after this manner, they brought the next to make him a mocking stock: and when they had pulled off the skin of his head with the hair, they asked him if he would eat, before he were punished throughout the whole body in every limb.

la: et habeo fiducia in pulchritudo tuus fornicor sum in nomen tuus et expono fornicatio tuus omnis transeo ut is fio
en: But trusting in thy beauty, thou playedst the harlot because of thy renown, and thou hast prostituted thyself to every passenger, to be his.

la: et reduco Israhel ad habitaculis suus et pasco Carmelis et Basan et in mons Ephraim et Galaad saturo anima is
en: And I will bring Israel again to his habitation: and he shall feed on Carmel, and Bason, and his soul shall be satisfied in mount Ephraim, and Galaad.

la: immolo vitulis coram Domino et offertor filius Aaron sacerdos sanguis is fundo super altar circumeo qui sum ante ostium tabernaculum
en: And he shall immolate the calf before the Lord: and the priest the son of Aaron shall offer the blood thereof, pouring it round about the altar, which is before the door of the tabernacle.

la: separo apud tu primitiae Domino omnis voluntarius et pronus animus offertor is Domino aurum et argentum et aes
en: Set aside with you firstfruits to the Lord. Let every one that is willing and hath a ready heart, offer them to the Lord: gold, and silver, and brass,

la: Ideo et credo de nos qui non probantur, et nolo inquiri, ne probo non sum qui malo credidisse, ut nomen ille aemulus ratio inimicus praesumptis, non probo crimen de suus solus confessio damnetur.
en: So they believe thing about u which are not proved; and they are unwilling for inquiry to be made, in case thing they prefer to have believed should be proved untrue; and the object is that the name, which is the enemy of that rival agency, may, because of crime presumed but not proven, be condemned simply on it own confession.

la: cum pertranseo dies plurimus et ibi demoror prospicio Abimelech Palestinorum rex per fenestra video is jocor cum Rebecca uxor suus
en: And when very many day were passed, and he abode there, Abimelech king of the Palestines looking out through a window, saw him playing with Rebecca his wife.

la: qui cum video armiger is videlicet qui mortuus sum Saul in-ruo etiam ipse super gladius suus et mortuus sum cum is
en: And when his armourbearer saw this, to wit, that Saul wa dead, he also fell upon his sword and died with him.

la: hic autem sum nobilis is qui sum Thessalonica qui suscipio verbum cum omnis aviditas cottidie scrutor scribo si hic ita sui habeo
en: Now these were more noble than those in Thessalonica, who received the word with all eagerness, daily searching the scriptures, whether these thing were so.

la: fors lignum et inputribilis eligo artifex sapio quaero quomodo statuo simulacrum qui non moveo
en: He hath chosen strong wood, and that will not rot: the skilful workman seeketh how he may set up an idol that may not be moved.

la: diligo odientes tu et odium habeo diligo tu et ostendo hodie quia non cura de dux tuus et de servio tuus et verus cognosco modo quia si Absalom vivo et nos omnis occumbo tunc placeo tu
en: Thou lovest them that hate thee, and thou hatest them that love thee: and thou hast shewn this day that thou carest not for thy nobles, nor for thy servants: and I now plainly perceive that if Absalom had lived, and all we had been slain, then it would have pleased thee.

la: Licet nunc sarmenticios et semaxios appelletis, quia ad stipes dimidium axis revincio sarmentor ambitus exurimur.
en: So you may now call u faggot-fellows and half-axle-men, because we are tied to a half-axle-post, the faggot are piled round us, and we are burnt.

la: festino et ascendo ad pater meus et dico is hic mando filius tuus Ioseph Deus ego facio dominus universus terra Aegyptius descendo ad ego ne morior
en: Make haste, and go ye up to my father, and say to him: Thus saith thy son Joseph: God hath made me lord of the whole land of Egypt; come down to me, linger not.

la: quis ergo amplus sum Judaeus aut qui utilitas circumcisio
en: What advantage then hath the Jew: or what is the profit of circumcision?

la: sicut visito pastor grex suus in dies quando sum in medium ovis suus dissipataris sic visito ovo meus et libero is de omnis locus quo dis-permulceo sum in dies nubo et caligo
en: As the shepherd visiteth his flock in the day when he shall be in the midst of his sheep that were scattered, so will I visit my sheep, and will deliver them out of all the place where they have been scattered in the cloudy and dark day.

la: et Dominus non ignosco is sed tunc quam magnus furor is fumo et zelus contra homo ille et sedeo super is omnis maledico qui scribo sum in hic volumen et deleo nomen is sub caelum
en: And the Lord should not forgive him: but his wrath and jealousy against that man should be exceedingly enkindled at that time, and all the curse that are written in this volume should light upon him: and the Lord should blot out his name from under heaven,

la: tu amicus meus sum si facio qui ego praecipio tu
en: You are my friends, if you do the thing that I command you.

la: ascendo autem Naas Ammonites et pugno coepio adverro Iabesgalaad dico omnis vir Iabes ad Naas habeo nos foedero et servio tu
en: And it came to pas about a month after this, that Naas, the Ammonite, came up, and began to fight against Jabes Galaad. And all the men of Jabes said to Naas: Make a covenant with us, and we will serve thee.

la: et nunc Domine Deus noster qui educo populus tuus de terra Aegyptius in manus fortis et facio tu nomen secundus dies hic pecco iniquitas facio
en: And now, O Lord, our God, who hast brought forth thy people out of the land of Egypt, with a strong hand, and hast made thee a name a at this day: we have sinned, we have committed iniquity,

la: et non inhabito neque inambulo et in ecclesia non transilient
en: And they shall not dwell, nor walk about therein, and they shall not go up into the assembly.

la: Hieremias autem fero volumen alius et do ille Baruch filius Neria scriba qui scribo in is ex os Hieremias omnis sermo liber qui conbuserat Ioachim rex Judas ignis et insuper addo sum sermo multus multus quam ante sum
en: And Jeremias took another volume, and gave it to Baruch the son of Nerias the scribe: who wrote in it from the mouth of Jeremias all the word of the book which Joakim the king of Juda had burnt with fire: and there were added besides many more word than had been before.

la: non possum arbor bonus fructus malus facio neque arbor malus fructus bonus facio
en: A good tree cannot bring forth evil fruit, neither can an evil tree bring forth good fruit.

la: nunc ergo filis audio ego et ad-tendo verbum ora meus
en: Now, therefore, my son, hear me, and attend to the word of my mouth.

la: sed parvus post tempus Lysias procurator rex et propinquus atque negotium praepono gravis fero de hic qui accido
en: A short time after this Lysias, the king's lieutenant, and cousin, and who had chief charge over all the affairs, being greatly displeased with what had happened,

la: Velocitas divinitas creditur, quia substantia ignoratur.
en: Their swiftness pass for divinity, because their real nature is unknown.

la: cognosco ergo quia propterea invenio ego malus iste et ecce pereo tristitia magnus in terra alienus
en: I know, therefore, that for this cause these evil have found me: and behold I perish with great grief in a strange land.

la: et dico ad ego Danihel vir desiderium intellego verbum qui ego loquor ad tu et sto in gradus tuus nunc enim sum mitto ad tu cum dico ego sermo iste sto tremo
en: And he said to me: Daniel, thou man of desires, understand the word that I speak to thee, and stand upright: for I am sent now to thee. And when he had said this word to me, I stood trembling.

la: Christianus uxor suus solus masculus nascitur.
en: The Christian is born masculine for his wife and for no other woman.

la: et audio rex ut libero ancilla suus de manus omnis qui volo deleo ego et filius meus simul de hereditas Dei
en: And the king hath hearkened to me to deliver his handmaid out of the hand of all that would destroy me and my son together out of the inheritance of God.

la: ZAI memoria memor sum et tabesco in ego anima meus
en: Zain. I will be mindful and remember, and my soul shall languish within me.
